// reso-2.0-canonical.dbml
// Pure RESO Data Dictionary 2.0 canonical schema (2NF normalized)
// 41 Resources, 1476 Fields kept (1745 total - 215 satellites - 54 Collection inverses)
// Lookup enums live in the companion file `reso-2.0-lookups.dbml`.
//
// Generated by reso-dd-kb/scripts/build_reso_canonical_dbml.py
// Source: dd.reso.org/DD2.0 + raw/fields.csv + raw/lookups.csv + raw/field_metadata.csv
//
// Companion files:
//   - wiki/dbml/reso-2.0-lookups.dbml    99 Enum blocks for SV lookups
//   - wiki/dbml/2nf-satellite-drops.md   215 dropped satellites by host+FK+target
//   - wiki/dbml/extra-fks.md             FKs detected via prose / name-shape

Project reso_canonical_dd_2_0 {
  database_type: 'PostgreSQL'
  Note: '''
    Pure RESO Data Dictionary 2.0 canonical schema: 41 Resources,
    1476 Fields kept (= 1745 total - 215 satellites - 54 Collection inverses).

    FK detection (4 passes, full algorithm in methodology.md Step 3):
      1. Resource-typed siblings  -> Ref host.<TargetResourceKey> > target.PK
      2. Definition prose         -> 'foreign key relating to the X Resource'
      3. Definition prose         -> "X Resource's YKey"
      4. Name-shape `<Word>Key`   -> Word names a Resource
    Lookup constraints are expressed as enum types defined in the companion
    file `reso-2.0-lookups.dbml`; no Ref: lines are emitted for lookups.

    Single-value (String List, Single) lookup columns are typed as the snake_case
    LookupName (e.g. `standard_status`); the matching `Enum standard_status { ... }`
    block lives in the companion file. Multi-value (String List, Multi) lookup
    columns stay `varchar` - DBML's type system can't model array membership -
    and tag their LookupName in the column Note. Open lookups (LookupName
    declared by RESO but with no closed value list, e.g. City, MlsStatus, AOR)
    are also `varchar` and tagged `(open: jurisdiction-defined)` in the Note.

    2NF normalization drops 215 satellite fields (full per-host list in
    `wiki/dbml/2nf-satellite-drops.md`). Collection-typed inverse references
    (54) live as `// Inverse 1:N` comments on each host table; the
    forward FK is emitted on the child resource by the four FK passes.

    No Atlas-specific decisions baked in. Atlas adapts this canonical in
    build_atlas_target_dbml.py (wiki/atlas/atlas-target.dbml).
  '''
}

